Dear Editor and Reviewers
First of all, we would like to thank the editor and reviewers for their very careful review, valuable comments and suggestions on our manuscript titled “SSPNet: Scale and Spatial Priors Guided Generalizable and Interpretable Pedestrian Attribute Recognition” (Manuscript Number: PR-D-23-01628). We have worked our best to address all concerns and revise the manuscript according to the comments from reviewers.

In specific, for R1’s comments, we fixed the formatting problem in the revised manuscript. We modified the figure of the AFSS module (Fig. 3). We added 6 papers in ''Related Work'' and ''Comparison with State-of-the-arts'' (Section 2 and 4.3). We provided more experiments on the PETA dataset (Section 4.3). We indicated the methods we test and the visualization method used for Fig. 1, cited articles according to the reviewer's advice (Section 1).

For R2’s comments, we included efficiency comparisons in the ablation experiments (Tab. 3). We clarified the benefits of the AFSS module over hard-coded methods and their interrelation. We conducted additional experiments using PLE-S without AFSS (Tab. 2), and we improved the clarity of Fig. 5.

For R3’s comments, we explained the "imbalanced learning difficulty" that confused readers in our paper, modified the expression to make it more comprehensible (Section 1), and gave a paper to support our viewpoint. We added experiments on computational cost (Tab. 3) and gave the results of the paper's experiments on cross-domain adaptation (Tab. 4, 7, 8 and 9). We tested the occlusion and scale deformation samples you mentioned and added difficulty case studies (Fig. 7 and Appendix B). We explained the innovations of the AFSS module compared to the feature pyramid. We explained the different effects of the three PLE modules on the results and illustrated the innovation of this paper. We presented the paper used for visualization in Fig. 1(Section 1). We explained the idea that the imbalance problem gives rise to incorrect location of the response of the heat map. We checked the whole manuscript carefully for grammatical errors and typos.

In addition, to improve readability, we have transformed Tab. 2 from the original manuscript into Fig. 6 in the revised manuscript. Our revisions have been highlighted in red within the revised manuscript.

Thank you with best regards,
All authors.
