5) As far as I can see, PLE-R、PLE-K、PLE-S are similar region extraction methods. Will different approaches have a differentiated impact on the results? Besides, key point-based method, region-based method even parsing based methods are not new in PAR. The author should clarify the novelty of this paper.
Response: Thanks for your nice advice. We respond to the questions point by point.
5.1) Will different approaches have a differentiated impact on the results?
There are 3 methods in the SPPNet family mainly because of differences in the use of PLE modules. SSPNet-R use the PLE-R module. SSPNet-K use the PLE-K module. SSPNet-S use the PLE-S module.
Differentiated impact on the results:
Recognition: From Tab. 3, SSPNet-S > SSPNet-K > SSPNet-R.
Speed: From Tab. 3, SSPNet-R > SSPNet-S > SSPNet-K.
Generalizability: From Tab. 7, 8 and 9, SSPNet-S > SSPNet-K > SSPNet-R.
Localization: From Fig. 7, 8 and Tab. 10, SSPNet-S ≈ SSPNet-K > SSPNet-R.
	Recognition	Localization	Offset points
PLE-R	Provide rough prior regions for attribute recognition to avoid the recognition results being interfered by irrelevant regions.	Constrain the localization of attributes to a coarse region.	✗
PLE-K	Provide fine-grained human body keypoints for attribute recognition so that attribute recognition is centered around the human body.	Provide fine-grained human key point and offset point cues for attribute localization.	✓
PLE-S	Provide sparse sampling points within the prior region so that attribute recognition is centered around significant areas in the prior region.	Give fine sparse sampling point and offset point hints in the rough prior regions.	✓
All in all, the PLE modules differ by providing spatial priors at different levels of granularity and whether or not learnable offset points are used.
