(1) Our innovation primarily centers on a novel approach that utilizes learnable offset points and attribute grouping to leverage spatial priors (region, human keypoints, and sparse sampling points). This approach addresses the challenges of extracting discriminative features and achieving precise attribute localization.
(2) Our AFSS module dynamically selects the optimal feature map scale during model training based on model results.
(3) We perform innovative analyses to assess the influence of spatial priors on weakly supervised pedestrian attribute localization, employing heatmap analysis (qualitative), IoU (quantitative), and correlation coefficients for both recognition and localization. For the first time, we conduct quantitative analysis of weakly supervised attribute localization using a clothing segmentation dataset.
(4) We achieve superior performance in pedestrian attribute recognition compared to previous methods and conduct generalizability experiments.

